{"text": "lead. The two components of the channel are the particle and hole of the Nambu space. The\n\nzero-energy Majorana mode, which has a particle-hole symmetric wave-function, appears as\n\na zero-energy pole of both g0(E) as well as gl(E). We can include this pole structure of\n\ngl(E), by approximating gl(E) near E \u223c0 as\n\ngl(E) \u2243(1 + \u03c4x)u2/E + a\u03c4z.\n\n(118)\n\nHere we use a Nambu basis where the particle-hole symmetry of the Green function takes\n\nthe form \u03c4xgl(E)\u03c4x = \u2212gl(\u2212E). Substituting gl(E) into Eq. 117 we get the amplitude of the\n\nelectron-hole reflection amplitude to be\n\nreh = Seh(E) =\n\n2i\u03c0\u0393[u2 \u2212i\u03c0\u0393a2E]\n\nE(\u03c02\u03932a2 \u22121) \u2212i\u03c0\u0393u2 \u2248\u2212\n\ni\u03c0\u0393[u2]\n\nE + i\u03c0\u0393u2,\n\n(119)\n\nwhere for the last step we took the limit of small a i.e. contribution from other states.\n\nNote that reh(E = 0) = \u22121, which is referred to the phenomenon of perfect Andreev\n\nreflection. This is a hall-mark signature of topological superconductors and indeed can be\n\nderived from the topological invariant103. In contrast, the non-topological superconducting\n\ncase, which does not have any such zero energy pole can be understood from Eq. 118 by\n\nassuming u(E) \u221dE, is characterized by an Andreev reflection amplitude reh(E \u223c0) \u21920\n\nthat vanishes. The reflection amplitude reh determines the reflection probabilty T eh\n\nii = reh 2,\n\nso that the conductance resonance for the Majorana mode is given by\n\nGMaj(E) \u22432e2\n\nh\n\n(\u03c0\u0393u2)2\n\nE2 + (\u03c0\u0393u2)2.\n\n(120)\n\nThis is the standard form for the conductance resonance associated with tunneling into a\n\nMajorana zero mode. What is remarkable is that the height of the peak is quantized i.e.\n\n47\n\n0.2\n\nE\n\nO\n\n0\n\n0.2\n\n0\n\n0.4\n\n0.6\n\nB (T)\n\n0.8\n\n1.5\n\nca\n\n1\n\n9RL\n\n(10-3e2/h)\n\n-3 0 3\n\n-0.\n\n1.2 ....!!!!!\n\n:!!!!!!.\n\n0.8\n\n0.4\n\n0.0 -0